<ChapterLayout title="Classified" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <h2>Running the Game as the GM</h2>
    <p>
      This chapter is for the GM. The rest of <a href="/table-of-contents"
        >Severed Story</a
      >
      belongs to everyone at the table; these pages are yours alone. Here is the toolkit
      for running a severed floor — the levers of standing and reward, the people
      and places that fill the world, and the events you can stage to bring a workday
      to life.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Players: this is the one chapter to skip.</strong> Half of the delight
      of <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a> is not knowing what your GM
      knows. Let them keep it.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>GM —</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >The game&#x27;s pages tell you how to run the floor. Mine tell you
            what running it really costs. I have hidden more in this chapter
            than anywhere else in the book. Watch for my notes — and the pages I
            have slipped in whole.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>The Break Room</h2>
    <p>
      Lumon may call it a place for &quot;reflection&quot;, if they mention it
      at all. I will tell you what it is. The Break Room is where they take an
      employee who has stepped out of line and have them read a statement of
      contrition aloud — again, and again, and again — until the words stop
      being words and start being true.
    </p>
    <p>
      For you, GM, it is the sharpest tool you have for raising the stakes. It
      is reserved for the serious transgression — the act that, were Lumon to
      discover it, could
      <strong>not</strong> go unanswered. What a visit costs, and how much, is yours
      to decide:
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Suggested Break Room Effects</u></strong></p>
      <p>Choose one, combine several, or invent your own:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The employee gains a quantity of <strong>stress</strong> of your choosing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The employee rolls with <strong>Hesitance</strong>
            for the remainder of the current workday, and/or the whole of the next.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The strain cracks something loose — the employee experiences a flash
            of <strong>outie memory</strong>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The employee loses <strong>Kier Points</strong>, gains a <strong
              >demerit</strong
            >, or the department loses
            <strong>Departmental Standing</strong>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            A lasting mark: a changed demeanor, a haunted look, a new fear the
            employee cannot explain.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The Break Room does <em>not</em>
      automatically grant a
      <strong>Wellness Session</strong>
      afterward. Whether one follows is up to you.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >Use it rarely. The Break Room loses its teeth if it becomes
            routine. Its horror lives in the anticipation — make the players
            dread the door long before you ever open it.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >And yes, I understand this is dark. But the world must be made to
            understand the truth, and this game is the only surface area I can
            find right now to share these uncomfortable realities.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2>Departmental Standing</h2>
    <p>
      A department is judged by the individual, <strong>and</strong> as a whole. As
      such, Lumon measures a team&#x27;s collective reputation as its
      <strong>Departmental Standing</strong>: a single rating, shared by
      everyone in the department, that sets how much oversight the floor
      receives.
    </p>
    <p>
      Departmental Standing is tracked on the <strong>LIEP</strong>, and is
      raised or lowered by you. There are five levels.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>V — Exemplary.</strong>
            A model for the company. Doors stand open, oversight is light, and the
            team moves with remarkable freedom.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>IV — Commendable.</strong>
            A trusted department in good standing. Routine oversight only.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>III — Satisfactory.</strong>
            Acceptable and unremarkable. Standard oversight. The default for most
            departments.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>II — Probationary.</strong>
            The department is under added scrutiny. New security cameras are introduced.
            Hallway privileges are revoked.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>I — Censured.</strong>
            The department is closely watched at every turn. Movement is restricted
            and privileges are suspended until trust is rebuilt.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      A department typically begins at <strong>IV — Commendable</strong>,
      enjoying the benefit of the doubt afforded to fresh hires. You may begin a
      campaign at any level the story demands.
    </p>
    <h3>Raising and Lowering Standing</h3>
    <p>
      When any member of the department is caught acting against Lumon&#x27;s
      interests, you may drop Departmental Standing by one level, among other
      things.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em>The crucial word is <strong>caught</strong>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      You may also want to speak to your players as to <strong>why</strong> they would
      even wish to be roleplaying in such a negative way.
    </p>
    <p>
      Standing rises more slowly: through sustained compliance, exemplary
      quarterly results, or a visible act of loyalty that restores the
      company&#x27;s faith. Raise it when the department has earned it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let the players <em>feel</em>
      their standing change through the fiction, rather than simply hear that a number
      moved. A dropped level looks like a newly-installed camera dome, a keycard reader
      where none was before, a corridor that no longer opens. A raised level looks
      like a lock clicking open, a guard reassigned, a door left ajar.
    </p>
    <p>
      Remember, this is all to an innie's benefit. They crave structure and
      meaning in their actions. A higher departmental standing is one of these
      many rewards.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="info">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u>Individual oversight</u></strong></p>
        <p>
          How closely any <em>single</em>
          employee is monitored should follow from Departmental Standing — but the
          specifics are left to your narration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>Severance Chip Protocols</h2>
    <p>
      The chip is not only a wall between innie and outie. It is a set of
      controls, and Lumon holds them. Their game would never print what follows.
      I will.
    </p>
    <p>
      These are the documented <strong>Protocols</strong>
      — overrides that authorized personnel may initiate, under the right conditions
      and from the right terminals, upon any severed employee. How any one of them
      truly behaves is yours to decide; treat them as story tools, not stat blocks.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Overtime Contingency.</strong>
            Activates an employee&#x27;s innie in the outside world, granting the
            innie control of the body beyond the severed floor. Intended for emergencies;
            coveted by any innie who dreams of seeing the world above.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Glasgow Block.</strong>
            Keeps the innie dormant, ensuring an outie stays in control regardless
            of location.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Clean Slate.</strong>
            A complete wipe of the innie. Everything they were — every memory, relationship,
            and shred of self formed on the floor — is erased. A fresh innie wakes
            in the same body, remembering nothing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Goldfish.</strong>
            Disables the formation of new long-term memories while preserving basic
            function. The employee works, speaks, and moves — but each day, and sometimes
            each hour, slips away behind them.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Freeze Frame.</strong>
            Halts all motor function while leaving the mind awake. The employee is
            frozen in place, fully conscious, unable to move or speak.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Lullaby.</strong>
            Forces the innie to sleep. Considered risky — prolonged use is rumored
            to leak memory between innie and outie — and so used sparingly, if at
            all.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Elephant.</strong>
            The inverse of a wipe: restores or preserves memory, and may open the
            door to reintegration of innie and outie. Profoundly dangerous.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Beehive.</strong>
            Binds a group of severed employees into a shared, hive-like consciousness,
            allowing Lumon to direct the collective as one.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Open House.</strong>
            Permits more than one mind to inhabit a single body at once — a temporary,
            unstable coexistence of consciousnesses.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Branch Transfer.</strong>
            Relocates a severed employee&#x27;s innie to a different Lumon branch,
            scrubbing confidential knowledge in transit so nothing travels with them.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      This is not all of them. Invent your own — Lumon does. A single Protocol
      can be the seed of an entire campaign, or it can be left wholly
      unexplored.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>Guard the terminals.</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >A Protocol can only be initiated from a secure terminal in a
            restricted space — a security office, a control room, the Testing
            Floor. Take care your players never reach one by accident. A clever,
            desperate party
          </em><em><u>will</u></em><em>
            try. The fear of what they might do with that access — and the
            lengths Lumon goes to prevent it — is one of the strongest engines
            you have. Let reaching such a room be hard-won, dangerous, and
            climactic.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2>The People of the Floor</h2>
    <p>
      A severed floor is full of figures of authority, each devoted to the
      company and to the employees in their care. The system is light on
      numbers; rather than statblocks, here is how to bring the most important
      of them to life at your table. Play them as people with goals, not
      obstacles with hit points.
    </p>
    <h4>The Floor Manager</h4>
    <p>
      The heart of the team — warm, attentive, and endlessly invested in every
      employee&#x27;s success. They greet good work with genuine delight and
      meet shortfalls with heartfelt concern. Play them as someone who, more
      than anything, wants to be loved by their team.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >The wanting-to-be-loved is the trap. It makes disappointing them
            feel like a failing in
          </em><em><u>you</u></em><em>. Their pressure is </em><em
            ><strong>intimacy</strong></em
          ><em>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4>The Wellness Counselor</h4>
    <p>
      Soft-spoken and soothing. In a Wellness Session they share warm,
      comforting facts about an employee&#x27;s outie, helping the innie feel
      known and at peace. Play them as serenity itself.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >The comfort is interrogation. They make the cage feel like care.
            Their pressure is
          </em><em><strong>seduction</strong></em><em>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4>The Security Officer</h4>
    <p>
      Quiet, watchful, and ever-present. They speak little and appear when
      needed. Play them as a steady, immovable presence at the edge of every
      scene.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >They never explain, because they never have to. Some doors, once
            you pass through them, do not open again. Their pressure is
          </em><em><strong>force</strong></em><em>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4>The Visiting Senior Figure</h4>
    <p>
      An executive from above, descending into the floor like an occasion. They
      speak in the cadence of Kier and treat the employees as cherished family.
      Play their visits as events.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >They embody a hierarchy so vast and so certain that resistance
            feels not dangerous but absurd. Their pressure is
          </em><em><strong>awe</strong></em><em>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4>The Mysterious Outsider</h4>
    <p>
      Not everyone on the floor is quite who they seem — a visitor, a transfer,
      a face that doesn&#x27;t fit. Your wildcard. Play them as a question the
      players cannot quite answer.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >The players can never be sure whose side they are on — including,
            some days, their own. Their pressure is
          </em><em><strong>uncertainty</strong></em><em>.</em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
