    <h2>The Departments of the Floor</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      A severed floor brings together many wonderful departments, each devoted
      to the comfort, productivity, and joy of its employees. Build any of them
      into your floor, and place the players wherever the story is happiest.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Gladness &amp; Provisioning (G&amp;P).</strong>
          Ensures every employee wants for nothing — snacks restocked, supplies replenished,
          and spirits kept high.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Comfort &amp; Repose (C&amp;R).</strong>
          Tends the floor&#x27;s furnishings and its ambient calm: the chairs, the
          lighting, the soothing background hum.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Welcome &amp; Belonging (W&amp;B).</strong>
          Greets new hires and nurtures the warm sense of family that makes Lumon
          feel like home.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Harmony Assurance (HA).</strong>
          Smooths the small frictions between coworkers before they ripen, keeping
          the floor serene.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Gratitude Services (GS).</strong>
          Coordinates the awarding of prizes, certificates, finger-traps, and other
          tokens of appreciation.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Splendor &amp; Upkeep (S&amp;U).</strong>
          Keeps the corridors gleaming and the artwork bright, that the floor may
          always delight the eye.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>The Real Departments</h2>
    <p>
      The list on the page before this one is a pleasant fiction. There is no
      &quot;Gladness &amp; Provisioning.&quot; Here are the departments that
      actually fill a severed floor — the ones whose work the game would rather
      you forget while you sort its numbers. Place your players in any of them.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Macrodata Refinement (MDR).</strong>
          Refiners sort vast fields of numbers into bins by the feelings the numbers
          evoke — sorting, in effect, by the Four Tempers. The work is mysterious
          and important...apparently. Blue badges.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Optics and Design (O&amp;D).</strong>
          Keepers of Lumon&#x27;s craft: storing and restoring the company&#x27;s
          paintings, maintaining its color palettes and branding, and — behind a far
          door — producing the floor&#x27;s many fine objects. Green badges.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Wellness (WN).</strong>
          Where the weary are restored. Counselors guide employees through Wellness
          Sessions — soft music, gentle words, and chosen facts about one&#x27;s outie,
          all in the name of care. Doubles as covert psychological monitoring.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Mammalians Nurturable (MN).</strong>
          Within a rolling indoor pasture of living grass, a large staff raises and
          tends goats, assessing each against the Core Principles, summoned by the
          ring of a bell.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Choreography and Merriment (C&amp;M).</strong>
          Lumon&#x27;s musicians: a marching band of brass, woodwind, and percussion
          that performs for ceremonies and celebrations, marching the corridors to
          honor a triumph.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Distribution Supply (DS).</strong>
          The source of the floor&#x27;s goods. When a supply runs short, it is from
          here that a fresh one is fetched — some minutes&#x27; walk from any department.
          The staff size is unclear.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Disposal and Reclamation (D&amp;R).</strong>
          A department known chiefly by its name. What is disposed of, and what is
          reclaimed, Lumon does not say.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Janitorial and Hygiene (J&amp;H).</strong>
          The department charged with keeping Lumon clean.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      There are codes on the security directories no one will explain —
      <strong>CE</strong>, <strong>TA</strong>, <strong>W&amp;A</strong>,
      <strong>EQP</strong>, <strong>CL</strong>
      — departments seen but never named. Leave them as mystery, or make one the seed
      of a story. An employee transferred to &quot;TA&quot; with no idea what the
      letters stand for is a fine way to begin an adventure.
    </p>
    <p>
      And then there are the ones on no list at all, because their labor is
      meant to be invisible. Ask who cuts the melon for the melon bar. Who irons
      the waffles. Who moved the wall that was not there last week. I am certain
      these must exist:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Food Services.</strong>
          The melon bars, the egg bars, the waffles, the coffee carts — someone prepares
          them. A culinary operation must hum somewhere beyond the corridors.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Facilities &amp; Restoration.</strong>
          The corridors are not fixed — walls move, rooms are repurposed, the Perpetuity
          Wing gleams as new. A staff of builders and restorers must shape and reshape
          the maze.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Horticulture &amp; Grounds.</strong>
          The hallway plants are real; the goats graze on living grass. Something
          green is grown and tended down here, far from any window or sun — and someone
          tends it.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Any of them makes a fine home for a player who wants somewhere stranger
      than MDR — or a destination for a Ricken-aligned employee following the
      supply lines, the trash, or the night shift toward a truth Lumon would
      rather keep buried.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2>Spaces of the Severed Floor</h2>
    <p>
      A severed floor is a bright and pleasant place to spend a working day.
      Below are the spaces you may build into your floor, each with a note on
      its use at the table. Develop more of your own!
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Elevator &amp; Stairwell.</strong>
          The threshold between the workday and the world above.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Department Floor.</strong>
          The employees&#x27; home, and the work itself. The default stage for most
          scenes. It may look vastly different depending on what the department actually
          does.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Wellness Center.</strong>
          Where employees are soothed and rewarded. Calm lighting, soft music, and
          a counselor&#x27;s undivided attention.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Perpetuity Wing.</strong>
          A museum to the Eagan dynasty — part shrine, part history, part monument.
          A place to deliver lore.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Corridors.</strong>
          Bright, clean, identical, white. The cheerful maze that connects every other
          space.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Floor Manager&#x27;s Office.</strong>
          Where you meet with your manager for guidance, recognition, and the occasional
          private word of encouragement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Conference Rooms.</strong>
          The stage for meetings, reviews, and team gatherings.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>The Spaces They Don&#x27;t Advertise</h2>
    <p>
      And then there are the rooms Lumon would rather leave off the welcome map.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Break Room.</strong>
          You have read what it is. As a place on your map, it is the door at the
          end of the hall everyone pretends not to see. Put it somewhere the players
          must pass.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Storage &amp; Supply Closets.</strong>
          Mundane and overlooked, and therefore perfect — for hiding contraband, for
          stolen conversations, for finding what was not meant to be found. The resistance
          lives in the overlooked.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Unused Space.</strong>
          Dim hallways kept low-lit &quot;to conserve power.&quot; Offices emptied
          by &quot;corporate restructuring.&quot; Every floor has its dead edges,
          and something is always a little wrong with them.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Testing Floor.</strong>
          A restricted zone. Secure terminals. Protocols. Whatever Lumon is really
          doing down here, it is doing it there. Reaching it should be the hardest,
          most dangerous thing your players ever attempt.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <hr />
    <h2>Corporate Events</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      Lumon punctuates the workday with rituals of reward and celebration. Each
      serves a different purpose at the table, so these are offered as a menu to
      stage deliberately, rather than a table to roll on.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Melon Bar.</strong>
          A spread of cut fruit wheeled out to reward a productive stretch. The social
          hub of the workday — a natural stage for coworker beats, and a quiet chance
          to pass a kind word to a colleague.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Egg Bar.</strong>
          A more lavish cousin of the Melon Bar — eggs prepared to order, presented
          with ceremony. Reserved for a notable achievement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Waffle Party.</strong>
          The highest honor a department can earn. Lavish and faintly ceremonial.
          Dangle it as a goal; deliver it as a memorable reward.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Music Dance Experience.</strong>
          The Floor Manager wheels out a small music player and offers the team a
          moment of sanctioned joy — a short, supervised release.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Quarterly Review.</strong>
          A formal accounting of the department&#x27;s performance. A natural moment
          to adjust Departmental Standing, award Kier Points, or stage a public speech.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Team Mixer.</strong>
          Two departments brought together to socialize — comedy, tension, and the
          chance to make an interdepartmental connection.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Wellness Fair.</strong>
          A floor-wide event of relaxation. Booths, exercises, and gentle encouragement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>The Retirement Party.</strong>
          When an employee departs the company, Lumon stages a warm send-off in their
          honor.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
